{"id":"306191193_Clique_relaxation_models_in_social_network_analysis","abstract":"Clique relaxation models that were originally introduced in the literature on social network analysis are not only gaining increasing popularity in a wide spectrum of complex network applications, but also keep garnering attention of mathematicians, computer scientists, and operations researchers as a promising avenue for fruitful theoretical investigations. This chapter describes the origins of clique relaxation concepts and provides a brief overview of mathematical programming formulations for the corresponding optimization problems, algorithms proposed to solve these problems, and selected real-life applications of the models of interest.","authors":["J. Pattillo","Nataly Youssef","Sergiy Butenko"],"meta":["January 2012","DOI:10.1007/978-1-4614-0857-4_5"],"references":["315009950_Mining_the_Largest_Quasi-clique_in_Human_Protein_Interactome","314389795_Mining_the_Largest_Quasi-clique_in_Human_Protein_Interactome","257658028_On_inclusionwise_maximal_and_maximum_cardinality_-clubs_in_graphs","244957010_A_graph-theoretic_definition_of_a_sociometric_clique","233729906_White_D_Structural_Cohesion_and_Embeddedness_A_Hierarchical_Concept_of_Social_Groups_American_Sociological_Review_68_103-127","233251812_A_graph-theoretic_generalization_of_the_clique_concept","232621180_Crime_Data_Mining_A_General_Framework_and_Some_Examples","227120673_Reactive_Local_Search_for_the_Maximum_Clique_Problem1","225237245_Greedy_Randomized_Adaptive_Search_Procedures","222151359_Network_Structure_And_Minimum_DegreeSoc_Netw_5269-287","221608769_On_Effectively_Finding_Maximal_Quasi-cliques_in_Graphs","220980362_Massive_Quasi-Clique_Detection","220519988_State_of_the_Art_of_Graph-based_Data_Mining","220286218_Constructing_Organizing_and_Visualizing_Collections_of_Topically_Related_Web_Resources","220243844_Clique_Relaxations_in_Social_Network_Analysis_The_Maximum_k-Plex_Problem","220117856_Network_models_of_massiv